# Boot Model

## Philosophy

Inspired by seL4: the kernel is a mechanism provider, not a policy maker.
The architecture startup code (not the user) launches the kernel.  The kernel
creates exactly one privileged userspace thread — the **root thread** — and
hands it all initial capabilities.  The root thread is responsible for setting
up the rest of the system.

There is no `main()`.  There is no `ulmk_kernel_init()` in user code.

## Boot Sequence

```
startup.S (_start)
  │
  │  (arch-level: stack, CSA pool, BTV/BIV setup)
  │
  ▼
ulmk_arch_init()          ← internal; initialises MPU, tick timer, phys allocator
  │
  ▼
ulmk_kern_main()        ← internal; creates root thread, starts scheduler
  │                        DOES NOT RETURN
  ▼
root_thread(boot_info)  ← first userspace context; privilege = ULMK_PRIV_DRIVER
  │
  ├─ spawn mc_supervisor, timer_server, ...
  ├─ grant capabilities to driver processes
  └─ become MC Supervisor or hand off and block
```

`ulmk_kern_main()` and `ulmk_arch_init()` are **never** called from user code.
They are called by the architecture's `startup.S`.

## Root Thread Contract

The user provides exactly one function with this signature:

```c
void ulmk_root_thread(const ulmk_boot_info_t *info);
```

Rules:
- It is the **only** thread the kernel creates at boot.
- It runs at privilege `ULMK_PRIV_DRIVER` (TriCore PSW.IO = 1).
- It receives a pointer to `ulmk_boot_info_t` describing available physical
  memory, tick frequency, and initial capability slots.
- It must never return; call `ulmk_thread_exit()` when done bootstrapping.
- It holds the **spawn capability** (the right to call `ulmk_thread_create()`).
  It can delegate this right to other threads via `ulmk_cap_grant()`.

## ulmk_boot_info_t

```c
#define ULMK_BOOT_MAX_MEM_REGIONS  4

typedef struct {
    struct {
        uintptr_t base;
        size_t    size;
    } mem[ULMK_BOOT_MAX_MEM_REGIONS];   /* available physical memory */
    uint32_t  mem_count;
    uint32_t  tick_hz;                /* scheduler tick rate */
    uintptr_t csa_pool_base;          /* start of the CSA pool in SRAM */
    size_t    csa_pool_size;
} ulmk_boot_info_t;
```

The struct is valid only during `ulmk_root_thread()`.  Copy any fields needed
beyond bootstrap time before calling `ulmk_thread_create()`.

## What the Root Thread Typically Does

```c
void ulmk_root_thread(const ulmk_boot_info_t *info)
{
    ulmk_thread_attr_t attr;

    /* 1. Create the MC Supervisor (takes over thread-creation policy) */
    attr = (ulmk_thread_attr_t){
        .name       = "mc_sup",
        .entry      = mc_supervisor_entry,
        .arg        = (void *)info,
        .priority   = 0,
        .stack_size = 4096,
        .privilege  = ULMK_PRIV_DRIVER,
    };
    ulmk_thread_create(&attr);

    /* 2. The root thread can terminate — MC Supervisor takes over */
    ulmk_thread_exit();
}
```

## Constraints for Code Under This Model

- Never define `main()`.
- Never call `ulmk_kernel_init()` or `ulmk_kernel_start()` — these do not exist
  in the public API; they are internal to the arch port.
- The architecture's `startup.S` is the only place that calls
  `ulmk_kern_main()`.
- Thread creation before the scheduler starts is valid only inside
  `ulmk_root_thread()`.  All threads created there start simultaneously when
  the root thread calls `ulmk_thread_exit()` or blocks.
